{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1540"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1540"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.18,0.09,0.52,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1540"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28558"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2673"},{"type":"tags","id":"2758"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman, 15 weeks pregnant, presents to the Emergency Department with palpitations. She has no other symptoms and her pregnancy is progressing well without complications. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications aside from antenatal vitamins. She has a family history of ischaemic heart disease with her paternal grandfather suffering a fatal myocardial infarction at age 80.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is haemodynamically stable with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Examinations of cardiovascular, respiratory and gastrointestinal systems are unremarkable. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is seen on this ECG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Right bundle branch block","Left bundle branch block","Ventricular bigeminy","Ventricular trigeminy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPalpitations are common during pregnancy as there is increased cardiac output, decreased peripheral vascular resistance due to vasodilation, and increased heart rate. The ECG above shows alternating normal sinus and premature ventricular complexes, this is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular bigeminy\u003C/strong\u003E. Ventricular bigeminy is simply a pattern of ventricular ectopics (aka premature ventricular complexes (PVCs)) alternating with regular sinus rhythm. If you look closely at the rhythm strip (the ECG trace right at the bottom) you will spot that there is a normal sinus beat with a P wave preceding every QRS (which is \u0026lt; 3 small squares and appears normal) alternating with a broad QRS which is not preceded by a P wave. Final year medical students will note that this is an example of rhythm which on examination of a pulse would appear regularly irregular.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA PVC is characterised by the premature occurrence of a QRS complex that has abnormal morphology and lasts longer than 120 milliseconds (3 small squares). The T wave following a PVC is usually large and inverse polarity and a PVC is usually followed by a full compensatory pause. During a PVC, the contraction is initiated by the Purkinje fibres rather than the sinoatrial node. PVCs may either be unifocal - arising from a single focus and having identical morphology, or multifocal where there are multiple PVC morphologies. PVCs can also occur in repeating patterns, bigeminy as above or \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminy\u003C/strong\u003E referring to a PVC occurring every third beat, quadrigeminy referring to a PVC occurring after every fourth beat. A couplet refers to two consecutive PVCs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPVCs become more prevalent with increasing age and in the setting of a variety of aetiologies. These include structural cardiac disease, stimulants (caffeine, cocaine, alcohol), metabolic disturbances (hypokalaemia, hypomagnesaemia), certain medications (digoxin, beta-agonists) and physiologic states such as anxiety and pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPVCs may be a normal electrophysiological phenomenon and do not necessarily require investigation or treatment. However, in patients with underlying structural or electrical heart disease, may trigger the onset of re-entrant tachydysrhythmia and are associated with increased mortality. They may also be a sign of underlying cardiomyopathy. In patients with frequent PVCs resulting in symptoms a transthoracic echocardiogram would be a reasonable investigation to exclude structural heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG showing \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E would show an irregularly irregular rhythm with the absence of P waves and therefore is not the diagnosis in this case. Likewise, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft or right bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnosed when the normal QRS (not the PVC) is \u0026gt;120 milliseconds in duration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ventricular bigeminy refers to alternating normal sinus rhythm and premature ventricular complexes"],"references":["Farzam K, Richards JR. Premature Ventricular Contraction. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532991/","Massing MW, Simpson RJ, Jr., Rautaharju PM, Schreiner PJ, Crow R, Heiss G. Usefulness of ventricular premature complexes to predict coronary heart disease events and mortality (from the Atherosclerosis Risk In Communities cohort). Am J Cardiol. 2006;98(12):1609-12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17145219/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28558"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1540"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15350"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15350"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6ea5d9bb-4d39-4a58-901a-ba08d9dcad2f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6ea5d9bb-4d39-4a58-901a-ba08d9dcad2f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":447}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28558"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-22T12:34:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-21T08:02:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1540"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43545"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app